    "resolution_criteria": "The Supreme Leader of Iran is chosen by the Assembly of Experts.\n\nThis market will resolve according to the person who is named as the next Supreme Leader of the Islamic Republic of Iran.\n\nThe resolution of this market will be based on the first official announcement of the next Supreme Leader of Iran after Ali Khamenei.\n\nAny interim, acting, or temporary leader will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nIf Ali Khamenei remains the Supreme Leader of Iran or the next Supreme Leader of Iran is not officially announced by June 30, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, this market will resolve to “None by June 30”.\n\nIf the position of Supreme Leader is formally abolished — including instances in which the Islamic Republic of Iran ceases to exist, is replaced, or no longer maintains the office of Supreme Leader — this market will resolve to “Position abolished”.\n\nOnly individuals formally appointed to the office titled “Supreme Leader of the Islamic Republic of Iran” (or a clearly direct constitutional equivalent replacing that title) will qualify. Individuals serving solely as President, head of state, head of government, or in any other role that is not explicitly the Supreme Leader or a direct constitutional equivalent will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution source will be official information from the government of Iran. A consensus of credible reporting may also be used.",
    "outcome": "Mojtaba Khamenei",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThe succession of Mojtaba Khamenei as the Supreme Leader of Iran was fundamentally shaped by two sudden deaths that removed alternative paths and forced an accelerated timeline. First, the unexpected death of President Ebrahim Raisi in a May 2024 helicopter crash eliminated Mojtaba's primary rival for the succession. Second, the assassination of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on February 28, 2026, amid a broader military conflict, triggered an immediate succession crisis. Under immense pressure and facing existential external threats, the Assembly of Experts bypassed more senior clerics to select Mojtaba Khamenei, prioritizing political continuity and deep-state backing over traditional religious credentials.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **May 19, 2024:** President Ebrahim Raisi dies in a helicopter crash, removing the leading alternative candidate for Supreme Leader ([art_general_20240519_022_392d5b25]).\n- **March 2024:** Elections for the Assembly of Experts yield a historically low turnout of ~40%, with the Guardian Council disqualifying many moderate and reformist candidates, ensuring a body loyal to the hardline establishment ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]).\n- **February 28, 2026:** Ayatollah Ali Khamenei is killed, triggering an immediate succession process ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]).\n- **March 1, 2026:** An Interim Leadership Council is formed, consisting of President Masoud Pezeshkian, Chief Justice Gholam-Hossein Mohseni-Eje'i, and Ayatollah Alireza Arafi ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]).\n- **March 3, 2026:** During the Assembly of Experts' first meeting to select a new supreme leader, Israel bombs its building in Qom. The building is evacuated with no casualties reported ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]).\n- **March 9, 2026:** The Assembly of Experts officially selects Mojtaba Khamenei as the new Supreme Leader, prioritizing political stability and security state backing.\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe outcome was driven by a sequence of highly disruptive events. The death of Ebrahim Raisi in May 2024 ([art_general_20240519_022_392d5b25]) caused a major shift in the succession landscape by removing Mojtaba Khamenei's most prominent rival. This led to Mojtaba quietly consolidating his influence among the hardline establishment and the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC). \n\nThe proximate trigger was the assassination of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on February 28, 2026 ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]). This sudden event plunged the country into a crisis during an ongoing military conflict. The external pressure, epitomized by Israel's bombing of the Assembly of Experts building on March 3, 2026 ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]), resulted in an urgent need to project continuity and strength. Consequently, the Assembly of Experts, already stacked with hardline loyalists due to the heavily vetted March 2024 elections ([art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]), bypassed more qualified religious scholars like Ayatollah Alireza Arafi and Ayatollah Hashem Hosseini Bushehri, electing Mojtaba Khamenei because he held the critical backing of the military and intelligence apparatus.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\n- **Religious Qualifications:** A significant countervailing force was Mojtaba Khamenei's lack of advanced religious credentials (ijtihad) compared to grand ayatollahs. In Twelver Shiism, the Supreme Leader is traditionally expected to be a high-ranking marja' (source of emulation). This was overwhelmed by the political necessity to elevate a regime insider with security state backing, similar to how his father was elevated in 1989.\n- **Opposition to Hereditary Rule:** Ayatollah Ali Khamenei had historically opposed hereditary succession to distinguish the Islamic Republic from the deposed Pahlavi monarchy. However, after his sudden death, the survival of the regime took precedence over ideological purity regarding dynastic rule.\n- **Alternative Candidates:** Figures like Ayatollah Alireza Arafi and Ayatollah Hashem Hosseini Bushehri possessed superior religious credentials and held prominent positions (e.g., Arafi on the Interim Leadership Council). They failed to secure the position because they lacked Mojtaba's deep, systemic control over the IRGC and intelligence networks, which proved decisive in a wartime crisis.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: Death of President Ebrahim Raisi in a helicopter crash\n  - date: 2024-05-19\n  - why it matters causally: Removed the strongest alternative candidate for the Supreme Leader position, paving the way for Mojtaba Khamenei.\n  - source article IDs: [art_general_20240519_022_392d5b25]\n- E2: Assassination of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei\n  - date: 2026-02-28\n  - why it matters causally: Triggered the immediate and urgent succession process amid a national crisis.\n  - source article IDs: [art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]\n- E3: Formation of the Interim Leadership Council\n  - date: 2026-03-01\n  - why it matters causally: Temporarily managed state affairs and organized the transition, demonstrating regime resilience.\n  - source article IDs: [art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]\n- E4: Israeli bombing of the Assembly of Experts building in Qom\n  - date: 2026-03-03\n  - why it matters causally: Heightened the sense of existential threat, forcing the Assembly to quickly select a successor with strong military backing.\n  - source article IDs: [art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Death of Ebrahim Raisi | [art_general_20240519_022_392d5b25] | 2024-05-19 | 1.0 | Removed leading rival. |\n| Assassination of Ali Khamenei | [art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1] | 2026-02-28 | 1.0 | Triggered succession. |\n| Assembly of Experts bombed | [art_general_20260308_023_c4db40f1] | 2026-03-03 | 1.0 | Accelerated selection process. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\n- **Internal Fractures within the IRGC:** It remains somewhat uncertain whether there was internal dissent within the Revolutionary Guards regarding Mojtaba's elevation. An alternative path could have seen the IRGC back a more pliant clerical figurehead like Arafi while ruling from behind the scenes.\n- **Popular Uprisings:** The swift succession was designed to pre-empt domestic unrest. A slower process or visible infighting could have provided an opening for widespread protests, potentially threatening the regime's survival or leading to a direct military takeover.\n",
